  "prompt": "Can Home Depot copy a car key with a chip if I provide them a blank key with a chip?",
  "response": "Home Depot can duplicate standard car keys, including some keys with transponder chips, but their services are primarily geared toward house keys and basic car keys without advanced security features. However, the ability to duplicate a car key with a chip depends on several factors:\n\n1. **Compatibility of the Blank Key**: Home Depot may not have the equipment or capability to program a blank key with a transponder chip to match your vehicle's immobilizer system. Programming a chipped key typically requires specialized tools and access to your car's onboard computer.\n\n2. **Type of Key**: Some modern car keys, especially those with advanced features like push-to-start or proximity sensors, may require programming by a dealership or a specialized locksmith.\n\n3. **Store Availability**: Not all Home Depot locations have the same equipment or services. Some may offer more advanced key duplication services, while others may not.\n\nIf your car key has a transponder chip, it\u2019s often best to consult a dealership or a professional automotive locksmith who specializes in programming chipped keys. They will have the necessary equipment and expertise to ensure the key works correctly with your vehicle\u2019s immobilizer system.",
